{
  "doc_id": "43368",
  "text": "Neurofibromatosis type-1 (NF-1) is a dominantly inherited genetic disorder with age-dependent penetrance and highly variable expressivity [CITATION_1] . The causative gene NF1, located in 17q11.2, is a tumour suppressor gene, which encodes neurofibromin. Neurofibromin negatively regulates RAS by converting it from the active GTPbound form to the inactive GDP-bound form [CITATION_2] . Loss of neurofibromin results in hyperactivation of the RAS proto-oncogene, which is a key signalling molecule of cell growth. Therefore, NF-1 is now recognized as a form of RASopathy, where dysregulated RAS-MAPK signalling pathway causes cancer predisposition [CITATION_3] . Pheochromocytoma/paraganglioma (PPGL) is one of the most common endocrine neoplasia associated with NF-1 Correspondence should be addressed to C-L Wong Email wcl264@ha.org.hk",
  "correct_citation": {
